column168: Description Of Events

FAULTY CONTAINER (MANUFACTURING DEFECT) ALLOWED PRODUCT TO LEAK FROM WHERE THE HANDLE WAS JOINED TO THE CONTAINER.  ALL SPILLED PRODUCT WAS ABSORBED WITH OIL DRY AND PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  ALL DAMAGED PRODUCT WAS HANDLED ACCORDING TO ALL LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. INSTRUCTIONS HAVE BEEN GIVEN AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TAKEN FOR ALL EMPLOYEES INVOLVED IN THE RELEASE.

THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE LEAKAGE WAS NOTICED. THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED, OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL 12 PLASTIC BOTTLES. THE CAP SEAL ON THREE OF THE BOTTLES FAILED ALLOWING THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE SHIPPER FOR DISPOSITION.

THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE DAMAGE LEADING TO THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL OCCURED. THE ITEM WAS APPARENTLY DROPPED IN HANDLING CAUSING THE WELD SEAM AT THE BOTTOM OF THE UNIT TO SEPARATE ALLOWING THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE SHIPPER FOR DISPOSITION.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  DURING A ROUTINE INSPECTION OF THE FREIGHT IN FONTANA, CALIFORNIA THE CONSIGNEE REFUSED TO ACCEPT THE SHIPMENT DUE TO MOISTURE IN THE TRAILER.  THE CONSIGNEE, OPENED ONE OF THE 2,205 POUND PLASTIC SUPER SACKS TO DETERMINE IF THE PRODUCT INSIDE THE PACKAGE WAS WET AND THAT IS WHEN APPROXIMATELY TWO OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  EXCEL TRANSPORTATION SERVICES, INC. CONTACTED H.M.H.T.T.C., INC. OF POMONA, CALIFORNIA TO PERFORM CLEANUP AND A FURTHER INVESTIGATION OF THE TRAILER. UPON INVESTIGATION OF THE TRAILER, H.M.H.T.T.C., INC. DETERMINED THE MOISTURE IN THE TRAILER WAS DUE TO WATER LEAKING INTO THE TRAILER. H.M.H.T.T.C., INC. SWEPT UP THE TWO OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT AND PLACED THE FREE PRODUCT BACK IN IT'S ORIGINAL CONTAINER.  H.M.H.T.T.C., INC. THEN USED DUCT TAPE TO RESEAL THE BAG.  THE SHIPMENT WILL BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

THE NATURE OF THIS INCIDENT INVOLVES A FEDEX EXPRESS AIRCRAFT THAT MADE AN UNSCHEDULED FLIGHT TURN BACK/DIVERSION. THE DIVERSION OCCURRED ON 02/14/2003. THE AIRCRAFT BLOCKED OUT AT APPROXIMATELY 05:37 (CST) AND WAS AIRBORNE AT 05:48 (CST). A LOADING DISCREPANCY WAS THE CULPRIT IN THAT A 1.4S SHIPMENT WAS FOUND TO BE LOADED IN AN INACCESSIBLE LOCATION ON THE AIRCRAFT. THE FLIGHT CREW WAS NOTIFIED ABOUT THE DISCREPANCY AND WAS ADVISED TO TURN BACK AND LAND THE AIRCRAFT. THE AIRCRAFT LANDED AND THE FREIGHT DISCREPANCY WAS CORRECTED. THE AIRCRAFT REBLOCKED FOR OUTBOUND DEPARTURE AND TOOK OFF WITHOUT INCIDENT.

ALL APPROPRIATE DEPARTMENTS NOTIFIED.  CN/IC HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDED FINDING TWO BOLTS ON THE MANWAY COVER LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT AND THE GASKET DAMAGED. TANK CAR GATX 7561 (LOAD OF SULFURIC ACID, SPENT) WAS HUMPED AT THE CSX TRANSPORTATION STANELY RAIL YARD ON FEBRUARY 10, 2003 IN WALBRIDGE, OH., AT APPROXIMATELY 0700 HRS.  CAR CAME TO REST IN BOWL AND WAS STRUCK BY ANOTHER HUMPED CAR, CAUSING PRODUCT TO SPLASH FROM THE TOP OF GATX 7561.  CSX YARD PERSONNEL ISOLATED THE TANK CAR.  SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND DISPATCHED RESCAR OF TOLEDO TO INVESTIGATE AND REPAIR.  RESCAR INSPECTOR FOUND THE FRANGIBLE DISC RUPTURED.  A NEW DISC WAS INSTALLED; THE CAR WAS SECURED AND THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.  NARRI SCORE: 40  2*(5+5+0) * (2+0)  CAUSE CODE: 441

SANTA ROSA COUNTY 911 NOTIFIED CSX TRANSPORTATION THAT A TRAIN IN A SIDING AT MILTON, FL HAD A STRONG ODOR COMING FROM IT.  THE CSXT CHIEF DISPATCHER ADVISED THAT TRAIN Q60210 WAS IN THE SIDING AND THE LOCAL TRAINMASTER WAS SENT TO INVESTIGATE.  A SECOND REPORT FROM SANTA ROSA COUNTY INDICATED THAT THE ODOR WAS COMING FROM A TANK CAR  IN THE TRAIN, ACFX 82863, LOAD FLAMMABLE LIQUID, NOS (CRUDE SULFATE TURPENTINE).  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SYSTEMS DEPARTMENT (CSXT HMS) DISPATCHED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INSPECT THE CAR.  CSXT HMS FIELD MANAGER ADVISED THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT OF THE HAZARDS OF THE MATERIAL IN THE TANK CAR AND ADVISED THAT EVEN THOUGH MATERIAL HAD A STRONG ODOR, IT WAS NOT TOXIC AND NO EXTRA ORDINARY OR SPECIAL ACTIONS WERE NECESSARY.  HOWEVER HE FIRE DEPARTMENT SHUT DOWN A PORTION OF US HIGHWAY 90.  CSXT HMS'S EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR INSPECTED THE ACFX 82863 AND FOUND NO INDICATION OF ANY PRODUCT LEAKAGE.  THEY ALSO CHECKED THE OTHER HAZMAT CARS IN THE TRAIN AND FOUND NO EVIDENCE OF ANY PRODUCT LEAKAGE FROM ANY OF THEM.  HIGHWAY 90 WAS THEN OPENED AFTER HAVING BEEN SHUT DOWN FOR APPROXIMATELY 2 HOURS.  THE STATE OF FLORIDA AND THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WERE NOTIFIED OF THE HIGHWAY CLOSURE AND THAT THERE WAS NO PRODUCT RELEASE.  NARRI SCORE: 0 NO RELEASE # ERROR  CAUSE CODE: NO RELEASE

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE AT THE TERMINAL, FREE PRODUCT WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. DRIVER WAS AT UNLOADING FACILITY DISPENSING #6 OIL THROUGH A PUMP HOSE. THE PUMP HOSE BEGAN TO LEAK AND DUE TO THE PRESSURE GENERATED BY THE PUMP, IT SPRAYED 2-3 GALLONS OF OIL.  APPROX. (1) GALLON WAS ON THE GROUND AND THE REMAINING (2) GALLONS WERE SPRAYED ON THE SIDE OF OUR TANKER.  THE FACILITY WHERE WE WERE UNLOADING HAS AN ON-SITE CLEANUP CONTRACTOR AND THEY WERE IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE.  ALL OF OUR HOSES ARE CHECKED ON A REGULAR BASIS AND THIS TYPE OF RUPTURE CANNOT BE AVOIDED DUE TO THE FACT THAT WHEN INSPECTING A HOSE, A FLAW MAY BE IN THE HOSE BUT CANNOT BE DETECTED.  EACH OF OUR DRIVERS PERFORM A PRE TRIP, WHICH ENTAILS CHECKING THE STRUCTURE OF THE HOSE TO AVOID ANY UNNECESSARY PROBLEMS.  IF A HOSE IS FOUND TO BE DEFECTIVE, A DIFFERENT HOSE IS GIVEN TO THE DRIVER.

column168: EUGENE, OREGON SERVICE CENTER FOR CWX UNLOADER PULLED A PALLET OF FREIGHT BACK TOWARDS REAR OF TRAILER AND THREE PAILS OF THE ABOVE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SHIPMENT WERE STACKED ON THE WOOD AND TWO PAILS LEANED FORWARD, FALLING ON THE FLOOR AND SPILLING CONTENTS DUE TO LIDS POPPING OPEN DURING THE FALL.  THE AREA WAS SECURED BY THE MANAGER, THE CHEMICAL WAS IDENTIFIED, THE CHEMICAL WAS ABSORBED WITH "KITTY LITTER," ALLOWED TO DRY AND THE EMPTY PAILS WERE PUT IN THE SPECIALLY MARKED H/M AREA ON OUR DOCK ON A PIECE OF CARDBOARD.  PRIOR TO DOING ANYTHING WITH THE SPILL, THE MANAGER CALLED THE REGION SAFETY SUPERVISOR FOR CWX TO ADVISE HIM OF THE SPILL.  FUTURE PREVENTIVE MEASURES BY CWX WOULD INCLUDE NOT STACKING THE THREE H/M PAILS ON OTHER FREIGHT AND LOADING THEM NEAR THE REAR OF THE TRAILER WITH ALL FOUR SIDES PROTECTED BY DUNNAGE.  THERE IS NOT A HAZARDOUS WASTE FOR THIS SPILL.  THE KITTY LITTER WAS SWEPT UP AFTER DRYING AND DISPOSED OF PROPERLY.  THE CONTAINER IS NOT DESIGNED TO TAKE A FALL, SO IT IS NOT A PACKING ISSUE.
WHEN THE EMPLOYEE LOWERED THE DOCK PLATE INTO THE TRAILER HE STRUCK THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM CAUSING A SMALL HOLE AND RELEASE OF THE PRODUCT INSIDE.

RAIL CREW CAME IN ON TRACK #1 TO PICK UP AN EMPTY PHOSPHORIC ACID CAR.  ON TRACK #2 THERE WAS ANOTHER PHOSPHORIC ACID CAR PARKED FROM WHICH MATERIAL IS PUMPED DIRECTLY INTO THE GRANULATION SYSTEM.  ONCE THE RAIL COMPANY STARTED TO PULL THE EMPTY CAR, A 1/4" NYLON ROPE THAT IS ATTACHED TO THE 2" UNLOADING HOSE WAS SNARED AND PULLED, AND OPENED THE 2" UNLOADING VALVE HANDLE ON THE WEST UNLOADING STAND, LEAKING PHOSPHORIC ACID FROM THE CAR ON TRACK #2.  UPON NOTIFICATION OF THE SPILL, THE SUPERVISOR ON DUTY SHUT DOWN THE SYSTEM AND BEGAN PUTTING STAND AND LIME ON THE PHOSPHORIC ACID.  ALL OF THE PHOS. ACID WAS ABSORBED AND WAS CONTAINED ON SITE.  THE ABSORBED MATERIAL WILL BE USED AS FILLER IN THE GRANULATION PROCESS.  OTHER CORRECTIVE ACTIONS ARE TO REMOVE THE NYLON ROPE AND INSTALL A CHECK VALVE ON THE DISCHARGE SIDE OF THE VALVE AND INSTALL BRACKETS TO HOLD UNLOADING LINES TOWARD THE CENTER OF THE STAND.

AS OF THIS DATE,  THE TRAILER HAS NOT BEEN INSPECTED TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK. BECAUSE OF THE NATURE OF THE LEAK AND THE AREA IT APPEARED TO BE COMING FROM, IT IS ONLY SUSPECTED THAT THE LEAK WAS A RESULT OF A CRACK IN THE BARREL OF THE CARGO TANK.

column168: OVERVIEW: A RAIL CAR CONTAINING HYDROCHLORIC ACID, (HCI) RESIDUE WAS RELEASED FROM THE VERTEX DUPO, IL LOCATION ON 01/29/03 TO THE UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD. ON 2/14/03, VERTEX RECEIVED A CALL REPORTING THAT THE CAR WAS LOCATED IN THE MAYS RAIL YARD IN NEW ORLEANS AND VAPOR WAS RELEASING FROM THE BLIND FLANGE. VERTEX PROCEDURES/INVESTIGATION: VERTEX HAS A RAIL CAR PROCEDURE/ CHECKLIST FOR RELEASING CARS TO THE RAILROAD (RR). THE FOLLOWING PROCEDURE IS FOLLOWED BY THE OPERATORS WHEN UNHOOKING/RELEASING A CAR TO THE RR. ALL PRODUCT VALVE ARE UNBOLTED AND REMOVED FROM THE CAR. BLIND FLANGES WITH GASKETS ARE THEN ON THE CAR. IN THE CASE OF AN HCI CAR, VAPORS COME OUT OF THE CAR UNTIL THE BLIND FLANGE IS TIGHTENED DOWN, DUE TO THE VAPOR PRESSURE OF THE PRODUCT. TYPICALLY, THE CAR VENT WHEN THE PRODUCT VALVES ARE UNHOOKED. THE BLIND FLANGES ARE TIGHTENED IMMEDIATELY TO STOP THE CAR FROM VENTING OFF AFTER UNHOOKING THE UNLOADING VALVES. IT IS OBVIOUS WHEN THE BLIND FLANGES ARE NOT TIGHT, BECAUSE VAPORS ARE VISIBLE. BEFORE THE OPERATORS LEAVES THE TOP OF THE CAR ALL BLIND FLANGES ARE CHECKED FOR TIGHTNESS. THE AIR VALVE ON THE CAR IS VERIFIED TO BE OFF AND DOME BOLTS ARE VERIFIED TO BE TIGHT IF THE PRODUCER REQUESTS IT SEALS ARE APPLIED TO THE CAR. TIMELINE/WEATHER: THIS RAIL CAR WAS CLOSED UP ON 1/27/03, RELEASED TO THE UNION PACIFIC RR ON 1/29/03. THE HIGH TEMPERATURES IN THE AREA THOSE THREE DAYS WERE 50- 58F. THE CAR WAS NOT PULLED FROM THE DUPO AREA UNTIL 2/6/03. ON 2/2/03, THE TEMPERATURE ROSE TO 67F, AND ON 2/3 IT WAS STILL 64F, HIGH AND RAIN, HIGH HUMIDITY. HAD THIS CAR HAD A LOOSE FLANGE DURING THAT PERIOD, VENTING WOULD HAVE BEEN VISIBLE. CONCLUSION: IN VERTEX OPINION, THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT WAS A LOOSE FLANGE ON THE RAIL CAR. IT APPEARS MOST LIKELY THAT SOMEONE VANDALIZED OR TAMPERED WITH THE CAR DURING TRANSIT. FROM 1/29/03 TO 2/14/03 THE RAIL CAR WAS NO LONGER IN VERTEX CAR. VERTEX IS NOT AWARE OF ANY MECHANICAL MALFUNCTION WHICH RESULTED IN THIS LOOSE FLANGE.

THE DRIVER WAS IN THE PROCESS OF MAKING A BULK DELIVERY OF SULFURIC ACID TO A CUSTOMER'S SULFURIC ACID TANK.  HE HAD THE TRAILER UNLOADING HOSE PROPERLY HOOKED UP TO THE STORAGE TANK PIPING.  THE CUSTOMER'S AIR SUPPLY LINE (REGULATED TO 35 PSI) WAS HOOKED UP TO THE TRAILER.  THE DRIVER OPENED THE AIR SUPPLY VALVE ON THE TRAILER, THEN OPENED THE CUSTOMER'S AIR SUPPLY LINE TO THE TRAILER (IT WAS PRESSURIZED TO 10 PSI AT THE TIME).  HE WENT TO THE REAR OF THE TRAILER AND OPENED THE TRAILER'S HYDRAULICALLY ACTUATED PRODUCT SUPPLY VALVE.  HE THEN OPENED THE SECONDARY PRODUCT SUPPLY VALVE, AND IN LESS THAN A MINUTE, WAS AWARE OF A LEAK SOMEWHERE IN THE ACID UNLOADING LINE.  HE SHUT OFF THE AIR SUPPLY, CLIMBED TO THE TOP OF HIS UNIT USING THE LADDER AND FOUND A GASKET BETWEEN THE UNLOADING VALVE AND THE TRAILER HAD FAILED.  ONCE THE TRAILER WAS DEPRESSURIZED, CLEAN UP PROCEDURES WERE STARTED.  A QUALIFIED TRAILER MECHANIC WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE TO REPAIR THE FLANGED JOINT WHERE THE GASKET HAD FAILED.  UPON COMPLETION OF THE CLEAN-UP AND REPAIRS, THE SULFURIC ACID WAS SAFELY TRANSFERRED INTO THE STORAGE TANK.  THE TRAILER WAS RETURNED TO PVS CHEMICAL SOLUTIONS IN BUFFALO, NEW YORK AND TAKEN TO A TANK WASH.  AFTER THE TRAILER WAS WASHED OUT, IT WAS INSPECTED & TESTED BY TRAINED MECHANICS AS A PREVENTATIVE MEASURE.

column168: WHILE TRANSITING THE PENNSYLVANIA TURNPIKE, THE CARRIER'S TEAM DRIVER WAS ADVISED BY CB RADIO THAT HIS TRAILER APPEARED TO HAVE A TIRE FIRE.  THE DRIVER MOVED HIS VEHICLE TO THE SIDE OF THE ROAD AND FOUND A FIRE IN THE TRAILER AXLE AT THE WHEEL END.  HE ATTEMPTED TO PUT THE FIRE OUT USING A HAND EXTINGUISHER.  EVEN AFTER EXPENDING THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE EXTINGUISHER THE FIRE DID NOT GO OUT.  IN THE MEANTIME HIS PARTNER NOTIFIED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT.  THE DRIVER DISCONNECTED THE TRACTOR FROM THE TRAILER AND MOVED THE TRACTOR A SAFE DISTANCE AWAY.  PRIOR TO THE FIRE DEPARTMENT'S ARRIVAL THE TRAILER BECAME FULLY INVOLVED IN FIRE.  HERSHEY, PA. FIRE DEPT. AND THE DAUPHIN COUNTY HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONSE TEAM RESPONDED.  UPON LEARNING THAT AMONG THE CONTENTS OF THE VEHICLE WAS A SHIPMENT OF TWO TOTES OF A PESTICIDE, THEY MADE A DECISION TO ALLOW THE TRAILER TO BURN.  THIS WAS DONE IN ORDER TO CONSUME THE PESTICIDES IN THE LOAD RATHER THAN PUT WATER ON THE FIRE.  ATTEMPTING TO EXTINGUISH THE FIRE WITH WATER WOULD RISK CONSIDERABLE ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE THAT WOULD RESULT FROM CONTAMINATED WATER RUNOFF ENTERING WATERWAYS.  THE CARRIER RETAINED A CONTRACTOR TO HANDLE MITIGATION OF THE INCIDENT.  THE TURNPIKE WAS CLOSED TO ALL TRAFFIC IN BOTH DIRECTIONS AT APPROXIMATELY 2000 AND REMAINED CLOSED UNTIL ABOUT 1730 ON FRIDAY, 2/7.  DURING THE MORNING OF 2/7, REPRESENTATIVES OF THE USEPA, PENNA. DEP, THE PENNA.  TURNPIKE COMMISSION AND THE DAUPHIN COUNTY HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONSE TEAM WHO RESPONDED MET WITH THE CONTRACTOR MET TO MAP OUT ACTIVITIES.  SEVERAL INCHES OF SNOW HAD FALLEN DURING THE NIGHT, COVERING THE BURNED MATERIALS ON THE TRAILER.  THE REMAINS OF THE TRAILER ARE TO BE PUSHED AS FAR OFF OF THE ROADWAY AS POSSIBLE.  THE CONTRACTOR IS TO DIG A TRENCH AROUND THE TRAILER IN ORDER TO CONTAIN ANY RUNOFF FROM SNOW MELT.  THEY ARE TO MONITOR IT PERIODICALLY.  IF IT FILLS UP THEY WILL BE REQUIRED TO EMPTY IT WITH A VACUUM TANK TRUCK.  THE EPA HAD BEEN CONTINUOUSLY MONITORING AIR QUALITY AND CHECKING FOR GROUND CONTAMINATION. NO CONTAMINANTS HAVE BEEN FOUND. A REPRESENTATIVE OF THE SHIPPER CONTACTED THE CARRIER'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SPECIALIST SEEKING DETAILS OF THE INCIDENT.  HIS QUESTIONS AND CONCERNS WERE DIRECTED TOWARD POTENTIAL AIR AND WATER CONTAMINATION, BOTH FROM HIS COMPANY'S PRODUCT AND OTHERS IN THE VEHICLE.  UPON LEARNING THE MAKEUP OF THE LOAD, HE EXPRESSED AGREEMENT WITH THE DECISION TO ALLOW IT TO BURN.

A FIRE DEVELOPED BETWEEN THE WRAPPER SHEET AND THE INSULATION ON THE CARGO TANK.  THE DRIVER PULLED TO THE SIDE OF THE ROADWAY AND TRIED TO PUT THE FIRE OUT.  THE ST. ROSE FIRE DEPT. WAS CALLED TO FINISH EXTINGUISHING THE SMOLDERING INSULATION.  THE DOT DELIVERED SAND AND A ARTIFICIAL DAM WAS PUT AROUND THE VEHICLE IN THE EVENT OF A RELEASE.  THE WRAPPER SHEETS WERE PULLED BACK AND THE CONSTRUCTION OF THE CARGO TANK WAS INSPECTED.  THE LOAD WAS TAKEN BACK TO SHELL IN NORCO, LA AND OFF-LOADED.  MODIFICATION ARE BEING MADE TO THE WRAPPER SHEETS TO PREVENT ANY PRODUCT TO GET IN-BETWEEN THE WRAPPER SHEET AND INSULATION TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER INCIDENT.

column168: THE DRIVER GAVE THE UNLOADING SUPERVISOR THE SHIPPERS BILL OF LADING WITH THE INFORMATION ON THE PRODUCT AND AMOUNT OF PRODUCT.  THE OKAY TO UNLOAD WAS SIGNED.  THE DRIVER AIR PRESSURED THE PRODUCT OFF THE CARGO TANK INTO STORAGE TANK.  THE STORAGE TANK INSIDE THE BUILDING OVERFLOWED INTO CONTAINED AREA.  CONSIGNEE PERSONNEL WASHED CONTAINMENT AREA INTO THEIR WATER TREATMENT PLANT.

ALTHOUGH THERE WERE NO WITNESSES, WE BELIEVE THAT THE DRIVER STARTED UNLOADING INTO THE WRONG TANK.  WHEN HE REALIZED HIS MISTAKE, HE CLOSED THE INTERNAL VALVE ON THE TRAILER, UNHOOKED THE HOSE, SLIPPED AND FELL WHEN HE WAS TRANSFERRING THE HOSE, WHICH CAUSED THE FUEL IN THE HOSE TO SPILL.  THE DRIVER WAS HOSPITALIZED DUE TO INJURIES FROM THE FALL.  NO FUEL RAN OFF SITE.  WEST CENTRAL ENVIRONMENTAL COMPLETED CLEAN-UP.

CONTAINER'S TARP RIPPED UPON GROUND IMPACT, SPILLING APPROX. 1/2 OF THE CONTAINER'S CONTENTS ONTO THE PAVEMENT. AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR ASSISTED IN SPILL CLEAN-UP & CAPTURED WATER RUN-OFF FORM PRECIPITATION THAT OCCURRED DURING SPILL REMEDIATION. column168: BNSF SWITCH CREW REPORTED PRODUCT ODOR EMANATING FROM TANK CAR IN RAIL YARD. RESPONDER TOOL TIGHTENED LOOSE BOLTS 3-4 FULL TURNS & RECHECKED REMAINDER OF BOLTS FOR TIGHTNESS IN STAR PATTERN. SECUREMENT COMPLETED AT 1745 HRS. CST 2/21  & NO FURTHER PRODUCT RELEASE WAS EVIDENT. SPILLED PRODUCT DAMPENED A 12-INCH SQUARE AREA ON TOP SHELL. TWO BNSF SWITCH CREW MEMBERS THAT ENCOUNTERED PRODUCT ODOR COMPLAINED OF EXPOSURE & WERE TREATED AT MEDICAL FACILITY WHICH PROVIDED OXYGEN TO EMPLOYEES WITH NO MEDICATION DISPENSED OR WORK RESTRICTIONS ENACTED. SHIPPER FACILITY TO IMPLEMENT PROCEDURES TO ENSURE THAT ALL FITTINGS & CLOSURES INCLUDING THOSE NOT USED, ARE RECHECKED PRIOR TO RELEASE IN TRANSPORTATION.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: OUR VEHICLE WAS INVOLVED IN AN ACCIDENT ON SNOW-COVERED ROADS CAUSING OUR TANKER TO TRAVEL APPROXIMATELY TWO THIRDS DOWN AN EMBANKMENT BEFORE ROLLING OVER ONTO ITS SIDE. THE TRAILER WAS LOADED WITH 7500 GALLONS OF #2 HEATING OIL OF WHICH APPROXIMATELY 540 GALLONS OF PRODUCTS WAS LOST ONTO SNOW COVERED, FROZEN GROUND. THE CLEAN-UP OF THE SITE WAS PERFORMED AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT. THE PRODUCT WHICH WAS MIXED WITH SNOW, ALONG WITH A THIN LAYER OF FROZEN SOIL WAS  LOADED ON TO OUR TANDEM BED TRUCK AND INTO BARRELS AND WAS TRANSPORTED TO OUR GARAGE LOCATED ON LINCOLN HIGHWAY, EVERETT, PENNSYLVANIA WHERE THE PRODUCT WAS MELTED DOWN AND CAPTURED INTO BARRELS. AT THE PRESENT TIME, THE PRODUCT IS BEING STORED AT THE SAME LOCATION AWAITING FOR RECOIL OF YORK, PENNSYLVANIA TO PICK UP THE PRODUCT AND DISPOSE OF PROPERLY. THE VEHICLE INVOLVED IS BEING STORED AT THE SAME LOCATION PENDING NOTIFICATION FROM THE INSURANCE COMPANY ON HANDLING OF THIS VEHICLE. WE WILL CONTINUE WITH THE SAFETY PROGRAM THAT WE HAVE IN PLACE. WE HAVE JUST AS RECENTLY AS THIS WEEK SPOKEN WITH OUR FEDERATED INSURANCE REPRESENTATIVE ABOUT THE PROGRAMS THAT THEY HAVE IN PLACE THAT CAN HELP US FURTHER OUR TRAINING AND SAFETY PROGRAMS.

ON FEBRUARY 27, 2003, ONYX INDUSTRIAL SERVICES INC. (OIS) SPOTTED LOADED TANKER 05-265 AT ONYX ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, LLC (OES) AT 2330 HOURS FOR OFFLOADING.  ON FEBRUARY 28, 2003 AT APPROXIMATELY 0300 HOURS AN OES EMPLOYEE NOTICED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE PRODUCT GAGE DURING HIS HOURLY TANK INSPECTIONS.  A PAN WAS PUT UNDER THE TRAILER TO CONTAIN THE MATERIAL UNTIL THE GAGE WAS REPAIRED.  ON FEBRUARY 28, 2003 AT 0700 HOURS APPROXIMATELY 2,500 GALLONS WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TANKER SO THE PRODUCT GAGE COULD BE REMOVED, REPAIRED AND INSTALLED TO ANOTHER TANKER SO THE PRODUCT GAGE COULD BE REMOVED, REPAIRED AND INSTALLED WITH NEW PACKING MATERIAL.  THE TANKER WAS RELOADED AND PRESSURE TESTED TO ASSURE THE GAGE WAS FIXED.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A REPEAT OF THIS INCIDENT, THE OIS DRIVER WILL BE REQUIRED TO CHECK THE GAGE AT EACH LOADING SITE AND WHEN DELIVERING TO OES, HAVE THE TOOLS TO TIGHTEN THE PACKING IF REQUIRED.
DURING DELIVERY, AN OUTAGE OCCURRED WHICH WAS CONTAINED, CLEANED UP AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.

column168: ON FEBRUARY 13, 2003, SCUDDER-TAYLOR MISTAKENLY DELIVERED 263 GALLONS OF NO.2 FUEL OIL TO 48 LAUREL ROAD CENTERVILLE, MASSACHUSETTS.  THE ABOVEGROUND STORAGE TANK (AST) AT THE RESIDENCE HAD PREVIOUSLY BEEN REMOVED BUT THE FILL AND VENT PIPES WERE LEFT IN PLACE.  THE OIL ENTERED THE BASEMENT AND IMPACTED SOIL AND GROUND WATER AT THE RESIDENCE THROUGH CRACKS IN THE CONCRETE SLAB.  THE MASSACHUSETTS DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION (MADEP) WAS NOTIFIED OF THE RELEASE ON FEBRUARY 13, 2003 AT 20:20 PM.  MADEP VERBALLY AUTHORIZED IMMEDIATE RESPONSE ACTIONS (DEPLOYMENT OF ABSORBENT/CONTAINMENT MATERIALS) AND ASSESSMENT ACTIVITIES TO DETERMINE THE VERTICAL AND HORIZONTAL EXTENT OF THE RELEASE.  MADEP AUTHORIZED THE EXCAVATION OF IMPACTED SOIL, REMOVAL OF OIL/WATER VIA A VACUUM TRUCK, AND APPLICATIONS OF FENTON'S REAGENT.  THESE REMEDIAL ACTIVITIES ARE ONGOING UNTIL THE ISSUE IS RESOLVED.

column168: UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK FOR FUEL OIL OVERFILLED.  2 WITNESSES FROM OUR ENGINEERING DEPARTMENT WITNESSED THE FUEL COMING OUT OF THE DIPSTICK HOLE. THEY IMMEDIATELY TOLD THE DRIVER UNLOADING THE TANKER.  THEY IMMEDIATELY STARTED CONTAINMENT MEASURES TO CAPTURE THE SPILL AND THE DRIVER STOPPED THE UNLOADING OF THE FUEL.  THE SANITARY SEWER LOCATED NEAR THE SPILL WAS DIKED TO PREVENT ENTRY.  THE STORM WATER RUNOFF HAD <1GAL OF FUEL THAT MADE IT TO THE DRAIN.  THIS DRAINS INTO THE EAST FORK OF ISSAQUAH CREEK. CONTAINMENT AND CLEAN UP CONTINUED AND MATERIALS COLLECTED.

column168: AFTER LOADING THE THIRD OF FOUR COMPARTMENTS AT THE CRANEY ISLAND FUEL DEPOT BOTTOM LOADING RACK THE OIL TRANSPORT DRIVER DISCONNECTED THE FACILITY LOADING ARM FROM THE TRAILER LOADING HEAD.  DURING THE PROCESS OF DISCONNECTING THE LOADING ARM THE 0 RING, USUALLY SEATED ON THE OUTER RING OF THE POPPET VALVE, CAME LOOSE AND WEDGED BETWEEN THE POPPET CLOSURE VALVE FROM SEATING PROPERLY AND THUS ALLOWING JP5 TO LEAK BETWEEN THE POPPET VALVE FROM SEATING PROPERLY AND THUS ALLOWING JP5 TO LEAK BETWEEN THE POPPET VALVE AND API ADAPTER BODY.  THE COMPARTMENT EMERGENCY VALVE WAS CLOSED TO REMOVE PRESSURE AND REDUCE THE FLOW OF JP5 AT WHICH TIME THE 0 RING WAS REMOVED.  THIS ACTION STOPPED THE LEAK.  THE TRAILER WAS DIRECTED TO STOP THE COMPANY REPAIR SHOP WHERE A NEW API ADAPTER WAS INSTALLED.

column168: ON NOVEMBER 18, 2003, OLIN CORP ADVISED CSX TRANSPORTATION OF A CONDITION REPORTED TO THEM BY THEIR CUSTOMER, E I DUPONT OF AMPTHILL, VA.  OVER THE COURSE OF THE PAST YEAR AND ONE HALF, DUPONT HAS DISCOVERED SMALL AMOUNTS OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE RESIDUE AROUND THE BASE OF THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE (PRD) ON 39 TANK CARS AFTER THEY HAD BEEN UNLOADED AT THE AMPTHILL, VA FACILITY.  ALL OF THE CARS ARE EQUIPPED WITH MIDLAND EXTERNAL PRD AND THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE TO INDICATE THE RESIDUE PRESENT WAS THE RESULT OF A PRODUCT RELEASE DURING TRANSPORTATION.  OLIN INSPECTED AND TESTED SEVERAL OF THE PRD'S AND FOUND NO MECHANICAL PROBLEMS OR DEFECTS WITH THEM.  OLIN REQUESTED CSXT'S ASSISTANCE TO REVIEW THE ROUTING AND HANDLING OF THEIR TANK CARS TRANSPORTED TO DUPONT'S  AMPTHILL, VA PLANT.  THE ROUTING INDICATED THE CARS SHIPPED FROM OLIN'S NIAGARA FALLS, NY PLANT WERE SWITCHED AT CSXT'S RAIL YARDS IN NIAGARA FALLS, NY, SELKIRK, NY, RICHMOND, VA, AND BELLWOOD, VA FOR DELIVERY TO DUPONT AT AMPTHILL.  THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE FROM CSXT, DUPONT OR OLIN THAT ANY OF THE CARS IN QUESTION HAD EXPERIENCED ANY UNUSUAL HANDLING OR HARD COUPLING'S IN TRANSIT.  CSXT WITH OLIN'S CORPORATION HAD INITIATED A PLAN TO EQUIP SEVERAL TANK CARS WITH IMPACT RECORDERS THAT WILL MONITOR COUPLING IMPACTS TO DETERMINE IF CAR HANDLING COULD BE A CONTRIBUTING FACTOR IN A POSSIBLE PRODUCT RELEASE FROM THE PRD'S. THE STUDY WILL BEGIN THE LATTER PART OF DECEMBER AND WILL CONTINUE INTO THE FIRST QUARTER OF 2004.  EVEN THOUGH THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE THAT THE RESIDUE DISCOVERED AROUND THE PRD'S WAS DUE TO A PRODUCT RELEASE IN TRANSIT, CSXT IS SUBMITTING THIS REPORT IN ACCORDANCE WITH SECTION 171.16 OF THE US DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION HAZARDOUS MATERIALS REGULATIONS, 49 CFR.

column168: DRIVER MADE A WRONG TURN ON WAY TO COAST GAS, CHICO AND ENTERED A COMMERCIAL BUSINESS PARKING LOT TO TURN AROUND.  WHEN HE TURNED, HE JACKKNIFED THE TRAILER AND TIPPED IT OVER.  THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER STRUCK THE FRAME RAIL ON THE REAR OF THE TRUCK PUNCTURING IT.  THE RESULTING EXPLOSION BURNED THE TRAILER AND THE CAB OF THE TRUCK.  THE TRUCK TANK DID NOT BURST, BUT VENTED.  WHEN THE TRAILER'S CONTENTS BURNED OUT, THE FIRE WAS TOTALLY EXTINGUISHED.  THREE HUNDRED FIFTY GALLONS OF PROPANE WERE RECOVERED FROM THE TRUCK TANK.  WHEN THE INCIDENT OCCURRED, THE DISPATCHER, IN SHAFTER WAS NOTIFIED BY PHONE AND I, JERRY LEES WAS GIVEN THE CALL.  I CALLED GENERAL MANAGER, DON PEDIGO AND ASSISTANT MANAGER GARY REED, BOTH TRAINED AND EXPERIENCED IN HAZMAT RESPONSE.  THEY PROCEEDED IMMEDIATELY TO THE SCENE.  LOCAL AUTHORITIES HAD ALREADY CALLED IN EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL.

TANK CAR GATX 61000 ON TRAIN MNPVP 20 WAS REPORTING LEAKING BY A PASSING TRAIN.  THE TRAIN WAS STOPPED AT MILEPOST 147.20 AND INSPECTED WHERE IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE TANK CAR WAS LEAKING FROM 3 HOLES ON THE LEFT SIDE OF THE CAR, TWO THIRDS OF THE WAY TOWARDS THE "A" END, HALF WAY UP THE CAR. THE HOLES WERE LOCATED ON THE UPPER WELD OF A WELDED PATCH. MARK REIMERS, REGIONAL MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED, ARRIVED ON SCENE AND REPORTED THAT APPROXIMATELY 500 GALLONS WERE RELEASED AT MILE POST 199.75, APPROXIMATELY 500 GALLONS HAD BEEN RELEASED AT MILEPOST 147.20 AND APPROXIMATELY 5500 GALLONS HAD BEEN RELEASED ON GRAND ISLAND YARD TRACK NORTH 2.  THE REMAINING CONTENTS OF THE CAR WERE TRANSLOADED TO POLYURETHANE TANKS.  THE TRANSFER WAS COMPLETED AT 2:00 AM ON FEBRUARY 22. FINAL CLEANUP OF THE SPILL SITES WAS ACCOMPLISHED BY 6:00 PMON FEBRUARY 25. THE CLEANUP RESULTED IN DISPOSAL OF APPROXIMATELY 100 YARDS OF CONTAMINATED SOIL AND 100 GALLONS OF CONTAMINATED LIQUID.  THE WASTE WAS DISPOSED OF WITH THE APPROVAL OF THE STATE OF NEBRASKA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY.  FURTHER INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT THE TANKCAR HAD FAILED A SPARK TEST AT THE GATX FACILITY IN WEST COLTON, CA.  GATX SENT THE CAR TO FRIT RAIL REPAIR SHOP AT BREWTON, AL. FOR FURTHER EXAMINATION.  THE TANKCAR NEVER REACHED THE REPAIR SHOP BECAUSE IT WAS TURNED AROUND ENROUTE BY A CONNECTING CARRIER.  THE TANK CAR WAS SUBSEQUENTLY RELOADED AND SHIPPED TWICE.

column168: ENERGY DISPATCH DRIVER MARLON HIGDON STARTED HIS SHIFT AT APPROXIMATELY 01:00AM ON 2/10/03. GAS STATION, THE DRIVER FELL ASLEEP CAUSING THE TRACTOR TRAILER TO HIT A UTILITY POLE AND OVERTURN.  DECHERD POLICE DEPARTMENT WAS THE FIRST TO ARRIVE AT THE SCENE OF THE ACCIDENT FOLLOWED BY THE DECHERD FIRE DEPARTMENT AND AEDC'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS UNIT.  THE 2900-GALLON COMPARTMENT OF THE TANKER WAS RUPTURED SPILLING APPROXIMATELY 1200 GALLONS OF 87-OCTANE GASOLINE INTO A DITCH.  THE REMAINING GASOLINE IN THE FOUR OTHER COMPARTMENTS OF THE TANKER WAS PUMPED OUT BY ANOTHER ENERGY DISPATCH, LLC TRACTOR-TRAILER.  FIRST RESPONSE, INC (TENNESSEE) COMPLETED THE INITIAL CLEAN UP OF GASOLINE AND WILL CONTINUE TO CLEAN UP PROCESS UNTIL IT IS COMPLETE.  AN INDEPENDENT ACCIDENT RECONSTRUCTIONIST WAS HIRED BY ENERGY DISPATCH, LLC TO GAIN AS MUCH INFORMATION AS POSSIBLE ABOUT THE ACCIDENT IN ORDER TO PREVENT ANOTHER SUCH INCIDENT OCCURRING.  IN ADDITION, MR. GLEN SUMMERS OF THE DECHERD POLICE DEPARTMENT, ALSO AN ACCIDENT RECONSTRUCTIONIST, INVESTIGATED THE ACCIDENT.  AT THIS TIME IT HAS BEEN DETERMINED THAT SPEED WAS NOT A CONTRIBUTING FACTOR IN THE ACCIDENT.

column168: UNIVAR DRIVER RUSSELL HOWELL WAS TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND ON INTERSTATE 81, JUST NORTH OF WINCHESTER, VA, WHEN HE EXPERIENCED A MAJOR TRAFFIC ACCIDENT. CONDITIONS AT THAT TIME:  TEMPERATURE 20 DEGREES F, OVERCAST, SLIGHT WIND, INTERMITTEN PATCHES OF SNOW AND ICE ON ROAD SURFACE,  MR. HOWELL STATED HE WAS TRAVELING APPROXIMATELY 50-55 MPH (POSTED SPEED LIMIT 65 MPH) WHEN HE ENCOUNTERED A PATCH OF "BLACK ICE".  THIS CAUSED HIS UNIT TO SWERVE SENDING HIM INTO THE MEDIAN.  DUE TO THE ACCUMULATED SNOW AND THE SLOPE OF THE MEDIAN THE UNIT ROLLED ONTO THE PASSENGER SIDE WHERE IT CAME TO REST.  MR. HOWELL WAS ABLE TO EXIT THE TRACTOR THROUGH THE REAR WINDOW AND WAS UNINJURED.  THERE WERE NO OTHER VEHICLES INVOLVED AND NO WITNESSES.  THE CONTENTS OF THE TRAILER SHIFTED FORWARD AND TOWARDS THE ROOF.  THERE WERE THREE 330 GALLON IBC'S, A VARIETY OF LIQUID DRUMS (15 TO 55 GALLON), THREE PAILS OF CALCIUM HYPOCHLORITE TABLETS, AND ONE PALLET OF SODA ASH BAGS. NOT A SINGLE LIQUID CONTAINER SUSTAINED A BREECH, NO LIQUID WAS LOST.  ONE PAIL OF CALCIUM HYPOCHLORITE TABLETS HAD FAILED RELEASING 22 TABLETS ONTO THE GROUND.  EACH TABLET WEIGHS .3 POUNDS TOTALING 6.6 POUNDS.  THE RQ FOR THIS MATERIAL IS 10 POUNDS, NOT REPORTABLE.  THIS WAS CONFIRMED WITH SR. TROOPER M.F. QUINCE, VA STATE POLICE (VASP), MOTOR CARRIER DIVISION, INVESTIGATING OFFICER.  AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR AND TOWING SERVICE OUT OF HARRISBURG, PA WERE CONTACTED TO HANDLE THE ACCIDENT MITIGATION.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: THIS ACCIDENT OCCURRED ON FEBRUARY 25,2003. THE DRIVER OF THIS TRACTOR/TRAILER RIG DROVE INTO A HERD OF DEER THAT WERE CROSSING THE ROADWAY. THE TRACTOR HIT AT LEAST 3 SEPARATE DEER WITH 1 BECOMING ENTANGLED IN THE STEERING MECHANISMS OF THE TRACTOR. AT THAT POINT, THE DRIVER COULD NO LONGER MAINTAIN CONTROL OF THE UNIT AND IT EVENTUALLY RESULTED IN A ROLLOVER OF THE ENTIRE TRACTOR/TRAILER UNIT. THE DRIVER WAS NOT INJURED AND DID NOT REQUIRE ANY MEDICAL ATTENTION NOR HOSPITALIZATION. THIS ACCIDENT WAS THOROUGHLY INVESTIGATED AND WAS THE TOPIC OF DISCUSSION IN CONSEQUENT SAFETY MEETINGS THROUGHOUT OUR COMPANY. THE DRIVER WAS FORTUNATE TO HAVE SURVIVED THIS ACCIDENT. THERE WAS NO SPILL OF PRODUCT AND THERE WAS NO ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE AS A RESULT OF THIS EVENT.

column168: DERAILMENT, NO RELEASE, EVACUATION ONLY, TILX 190448 AND GATX 81143, FEBRUARY 11, 2004, NORTH EAST DIVISION.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1310 HOURS, WEDNESDAY, FEBRUARY 11, 2004 AT BARB SIDING, SEWAREN, NEW JERSEY, CONRAIL'S YPPR-08 SHOVED INTO BARB SIDING AND FAILED TO REMOVE THE DERAIL.  CONDUCTOR WAS DIRECTING MOVEMENT ON THE READ (SHOVING END) END.  TWO TANK CARS INVOLVED.  TANK CAR GATX 81193, NON-INSULATED, LOAD FLAMMABLE LIQUID NOS (ETHANOL, PETROLEUM DISTILLATES) DERAILED AT B-END (LEAD) WHILE COUPLED TO TILX 190448.  FROM IMPACT TO THE TILX CAR, A DENT WAS EVIDENT ON THE BL UPPER CORNER OF THE HEAD MEASURING APPROXIMATELY 2 1/2 FEET ACROSS. FURTHER DETAILED DAMAGE ASSESSMENT CONDUCTED BY AAR-BOE SENIOR INSPECTOR W. OERTLY AND CONRAIL'S MANAGER RISK MANAGEMENT ALLEN RICHTER INDICATED THE DENT WAS NOT AN ISSUE IN RERAILING, MOVING AND UNLOADING.  NOTE: INSPECTION AT THE TIME OF THE DERAILMENT BY AAR'S, MR OERTLY NOTED THE BOTTOM OUTLET 4" CLOSURE CAP WAS NOT APPLIED TO THE OUTLET NOZZLE AND HANGING BY ITS CHAIN.  MR. OERTLY REAPPLIED AND SECURED THE CAP WITH SUITABLE TOOL PRIOR TO RERAILING.  TILX 190448 AND GATX 81143 DID NOT RELEASE ANY PRODUCT.  FOR PRECAUTIONARY MEASURES, APPROXIMATELY 22 HOMES WERE EVACUATED BY LOCAL EMERGENCY SERVICES.  TERRA ARRIVED AT THE SITE AND RERAILED THE CARS.  THE TANK CARS WERE RERAILED AND SENT TO MOTIVA FOR UNLOADING.

AT APPROXIMATELY 7:10 THIS MORNING, KEVIN DUNN WAS OFFLOADING OFF-ROAD DIESEL AT LEHIGH CEMENT IN LEEDS, ALABAMA INTO A LOCOMOTIVE FUEL TANK WHEN HE NOTICED THAT THE PUMP HAD LOST PRESSURE.  HE IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN THE PUMP AND WENT TO INVESTIGATE.  HE DISCOVERED A PUDDLE OF FUEL UNDER THE OPPOSITE SIDE OF HIS TRUCK.  HE REMOVED BAGS OF SORBENT MATERIAL FROM HIS TRUCK AND STARTED BUILDING A DAM TO STOP THE FUEL FROM REACHING A DRAINAGE GRATE, WHICH RAN THE LENGTH OF THE AREA WHERE HE WAS PARKED.  HIS QUICK ACTIONS KEPT ALL BUT A VERY SMALL AMOUNT (ESTIMATED TO BE LESS THAN 5 GALLONS) FROM ENTERING THE DRAIN.  KEVIN CALLED BILLY PUCKETT WHO THEN CALLED ME.  I GOT THERE JUST AFTER TWO TRUSSVILLE WAREHOUSE EMPLOYEES WHO BILLY HAD DISPATCHED WITH MORE OIL DRY MATERIAL.  WE ALL IMMEDIATELY STARTED SPREADING THE MATERIAL.  WHEN IT APPEARED THAT THE SPILL AREA WAS UNDER CONTROL, I STARTED TRACKING THE DRAIN AND DISCOVERED WHERE IT DISCHARGED TO DRY CREEK, WHICH FLOWS PAST THE PLANT.  DIESEL HAD REACHED THE CREEK AND CREATED AN OBVIOUS SHEEN.  DRY CREEK DISCHARGES TO THE LITTLE CAHABA, WHICH FLOWS DIRECTLY INTO LAKE PURDY.  I NOTIFIED JOEL YEAGER, LEHIGH'S PLANT ENGINEER AND REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO HIM.  I ALSO BORROWED SOME ABSORBENT 'SOCKS' FORM HIM TO PLACE IN THE CREEK IMMEDIATELY WHILE WE WAITED FOR SOME TO BE DELIVERED FORM TRUSSVILLE.  WE PLACED THE SOCKS A THE OUTFALL AND THEN PLACED THREE BOOMS ACROSS THE CREEK OF TIED TOGETHER SOCKS TO TRAP ANY FUEL THAT GOT TO THE CREEK.  AFTER THE SITUATION WAS SECURE I NOTIFIED ADEM AND THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (NRC).  THE NRC TOOK A REPORT OVER THE PHONE AND ADEM SENT PAUL ROGERS FROM THE BIRMINGHAM OFFICE. PAUL WAS SATISFIED THAT WE HAD MANAGED THE SPILL TO ADEM'S SATISFACTION AND SUGGESTED THAT WE LEAVE THE BOOMS AND PADS IN PLACE UNTIL AFTER THE NEST RAINFALL EVENT, RAIN IS PREDICTED FOR THURSDAY OF THIS WEEK.  ALL OF THE FUEL UNDER THE TRUCK WAS PICKED UP BY THE OIL DRY AND WAS SHOVELED INTO DRUMS AND DELIVERED TO TRUSSVILLE FOR DISPOSAL.  THIS MATERIAL CAN GO INTO THE DUMPSTER.  LEHIGH'S ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGER WAS SICK BUT I TALKED TO HIM BY PHONE AND HE WAS SATISFIED AS WAS JOEL YEAGER.  CLOSE INSPECTION OF THE TRUCK REVEALED THAT A RUBBER HOSE UNDER THE TRUCK (TRUCK# 2308) HAD BEEN RUBBING AGAINST THE DRIVESHAFT OF THE TRUCK AND HAD WORN A HOLE IN THE HOSE.  RE-ROUTING OF THE HOSE OR BETTER RESTRAINT OF THE HOSE ON THIS AND OTHER TRUCKS THAT HAVE BEEN RECENTLY UPGRADED SHOULD BE DONE IMMEDIATELY TO PREVENT ANOTHER INCIDENT LIKE THIS.  ONLY APPROXIMATELY 20 TO 50 GALLONS OF FUEL WAS LOST.  PROBABLY LESS THAN ONE GALLON REACHED THE CREEK.

column168: DRIVER BRAD HENDRICK WAS PUMPING CRUDE INTO A SUNOCO TRANSPORT AT THE LEASE SITE.  THE SAMPLE VALVE ON THE BELLY LINE OF THE TRAILER WAS IN THE OPEN POSITION AND CRUDE WAS SPEWING OUT OF IT AS THE TRAILER FILLED.  BRAD FAILED TO INSPECT THE VALVE TO MAKE SURE IT WAS CLOSED BEFORE LOADING THE TRAILER.  IT WAS RAINING AT THE TIME, SO BRAD LEFT THE PUMP CONTROLS UNATTENDED TO SIT INSIDE THE TRACTOR CAB.  HE DISCOVERED THE OPEN VALVE AFTER THE CRUDE HAD SPEWED ONTO THE GROUND.
